Part I - Loan Data from Prosper¶

by Yan Li¶

Introduction¶

This data set contains 113,937 loans with 81 variables on each loan, including loan amount, borrower rate (or interest rate), current loan status, borrower income, and many others. By investigating this dataset, I hope to answer these three questions:

  1. Who borrow money through Prosper? Why do they want a loan?
  2. What affects the borrowers APR or interest rate?

Data Cleaning¶

After checking the features, there are some cleaning work to perform before I can carry out Exploratory Data Analysis. The list of data cleaning tasks is as following:

  • Drop the duplicated rows
  • Shorten the names of columns ListingCategory (numeric) and ProsperRating (Alpha)
  • Change ListingNumber column to string type
  • Change ListingCreationDate column to datetime type
  • Change ProsperRating (Alpha) and EmploymentStatus columns to category type with specific order
  • In column LoanStatus, combine all options with "Past Due" followed by a delinquency bucket as one new option "Past Due"
  • Change LoanStatus, ListingCategory (numeric), Occupation, and Term columns as category type

Cleaning step 4: Change the datatype of LoanStatus and ProsperRating as category with specified orders¶

In [8]:
# Replace null values in column `ProsperRating` by "N/A" because this feature is not Applicable for loans originated 
# after July 2009.
loan_clean.ProsperRating.fillna('N/A', inplace = True)
# Replace null values in column `EmploymentStatus` by "Not available"
loan_clean.EmploymentStatus.fillna('Not available', inplace = True)

# category orders of the specified columns
ordinal_var_dict = {'ProsperRating': ['N/A', 'HR', 'E', 'D', 'C', 'B', 'A', 'AA'],
                    'EmploymentStatus': ['Not available', 'Not employed', 'Other', 'Retired', 'Self-employed',
                                         'Employed', 'Part-time', 'Full-time']}

# Change the datatype of the columns as ordered 'category' type
for var in ordinal_var_dict:
    ordered_var = pd.api.types.CategoricalDtype(ordered = True,
                                                categories = ordinal_var_dict[var])
    loan_clean[var] = loan_clean[var].astype(ordered_var)

# Check the order and category names of the columns
print(loan_clean.ProsperRating.unique())
print('\n')
print(loan_clean.EmploymentStatus.unique())

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

There are 113,937 records in the dataset with 81 variables. 66 variables are numeric in nature, but two variables are ordered factor variables:

ProsperRating: 'N/A', 'HR', 'E', 'D', 'C', 'B', 'A', 'AA'
EmploymentStatus: 'Not available', 'Not employed', 'Retired', 'Other', 'Self-employed', 'Employed', 'Part-time', 'Full-time'

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

It is not necessary to explore every feature in these 81 features because not every feature are closely related to the answer of the questions asked at the start of this report. After research on loan approval through internet, I decide to choose some features from the original dataset to carry out my exploration. The rest of the variables will not be considered in this report. So the 10 main features of interest in my dataset are:

  • LoanOriginalAmount: The origination amount of the loan.
  • LoanStatus: The current status of the loan: Cancelled, Chargedoff, Completed, Current, Defaulted, FinalPaymentInProgress, PastDue. The PastDue status will be accompanied by a delinquency bucket.
  • BorrowerAPR: The Borrower's Annual Percentage Rate (APR) for the loan.
  • BorrowerRate: The Borrower's interest rate for this loan.
  • StatedMonthlyIncome: The monthly income the borrower stated at the time the listing was created.
  • ProsperRating: The Prosper Rating assigned at the time the listing was created between AA - HR. Applicable for loans originated after July 2009.
  • Term: The length of the loan expressed in months.
  • EmploymentStatus: The employment status of the borrower at the time they posted the listing.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

The other 5 features to help support my investigation are as following:

  • ListingNumber: The number that uniquely identifies the listing to the public as displayed on the website.
  • ListingCreationDate: The date the listing was created.
  • ListingCategory: The category of the listing that the borrower selected when posting their listing: 0 - Not Available, 1 - Debt Consolidation, 2 - Home Improvement, 3 - Business, 4 - Personal Loan, 5 - Student Use, 6 - Auto, 7- Other, 8 - Baby&Adoption, 9 - Boat, 10 - Cosmetic Procedure, 11 - Engagement Ring, 12 - Green Loans, 13 - Household Expenses, 14 - Large Purchases, 15 - Medical/Dental, 16 - Motorcycle, 17 - RV, 18 - Taxes, 19 - Vacation, 20 - Wedding Loans
  • Occupation: The Occupation selected by the Borrower at the time they created the listing.
  • MonthlyLoanPayment: The scheduled monthly loan payment.

Altogether I use 13 features to answer the questions at the start of this report:

  1. Who borrow money through Prosper? Why do they want a loan?
  2. What affects the borrowers APR or interest rate?

Univariate Exploration¶

Question 1: What is the distribution of LoanStatus?¶

In [12]:
# set color
base_color = sns.color_palette()[0]

# plot histogram of 'LoanStatus'
fig = plt.figure(figsize=[6, 4])
status_counts = loan_clean.LoanStatus.value_counts().copy()
type_order = loan_clean.LoanStatus.value_counts().index
sns.countplot(data = loan_clean, y = 'LoanStatus', color = base_color, order = type_order)
plt.ylabel('Loan Status')

for i in range(len(status_counts)):
    count = status_counts[i]
    per = round(count / loan_clean.shape[0], 3)
    plt.text(i+count+2000, i, per, ha = 'center', va = 'center')
plt.show()

Observation 1: The distribution of Loan Status¶

  • Nearly half (49.3%) of all loans were in progress when Prosper Loan dataset was done.
  • 33.7% of all loans were completed.
  • 10.6% of all loans were charged off.
  • 4.4% of all loans were defaulted.
  • 1.8% of all loans passed the due date.
  • 0.2% of all loans were in final payment or cancelled.
  • The failed loans (Changed Off, Defaulted, Past Due, Cancelled) account for 17% of all loans, which is the half of the percentage of Completed loans.

Question 2: What is the distribution of Borrower's APR or interest rate?¶

In [13]:
fig, ax = plt.subplots(nrows = 2, figsize = [8, 8])

binsize = 0.005

ax[1].set_xlabel('Borrower\'s Interest Rate')

plt.show()

Observation 2: The distribution of borrowers' APR and interest rate¶

  • The borrower's APR and Interest Rate follows the same pattern but the borrower's APR is always slightly higher than the interest rate because APR includes interest rate, service charge and other costs.
  • Most APRs and interest rates are in the range between 0.05 and 0.4.
  • For both APR and interest rate graphs, there are a spike at about 0.35. Apart from that, the plot looks like a bell curve.

Observation 3: The distribution of LoanOriginalAmount¶

  • The distribution is multimodal with peaks at 4000, 10000, 15000. There are also smaller peaks at 20000 and 25000.
  • The distribution is also right skewed which means a lot of loan are with the amount under 15k.
  • By using logarithmic scale in x axis, the distribution of this feature looks more uniform and more details in the range between 1k and 10k are revealed.

Observation 9¶

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

  • Nearly half (49.3%) of all loans were in progress when Prosper Loan dataset was done. But in the loans which are finished, nearly 2/3 are completed. The failed loans (Changed Off, Defaulted, Past Due, Cancelled) account for 1/3 of all finished loans.
  • The borrower's APR and Interest Rate follows the same pattern but the borrower's APR is always slightly higher than the interest rate because APR includes interest rate, service charge and other costs. Most APRs and interest rates are in the range between 0.05 and 0.4. For both APR and interest rate graphs, there are a spike at about 0.35.
  • The maximum value of StatedMonthlyIncome is 1,750,000 and it is an outlier which makes the plot significantly skewed. 75% of the loan applicants have monthly income lower than 6824. By setting the range of X axis to (0, 15000), more details of the distribution are revealed. Most loan applicants have monthly income between 2000 and 6000.
  • Some categories in Occupation is ambiguous. For example, "Professional" can include many other categories like "Computer Programmer", "Accountant/CPA", "Analyst" etc. The most popular occupation in the borrowers are "Computer Programmer", "Executive", "Teacher", "Administrative Assistant", and "Analyst".
  • More than half (58.9%) of the borrowers are employed. Adding the categories of "Not employed", "Not available" and "Other" together, about 10.7% of the borrowers have uncertain employment status. The percentage of full-time worker (23.3%) are much more than part-time worker (1%) and self-employed people (5.4%). Some categories of this feature are overlapping. For example, "Full-time" and "Part-time" can be included in "Employed". This design defect makes the analysis of borrowers' employment status less convincing.
  • Most borrowers are rated between "A" and "D" with "C" as the most often rating. "HR" is the worst rating and "AA" is the best rating, both of which remains lower than other ratings.
  • The top 5 categories to borrow are "Debt Consolidation", "Not Available", "Other", "Home Improvement", and "Business". Debt consolidation is far more than any other types which means a lot of borrowers in Prosper have already got debts and it is easier for them to get loans through Prosper than other places.
  • Altogether there are three options for loan term: 12 months, 36 months, and 60 months. Most loans (77.1%) last 36 months. 60 months option is the second popular. Only 1.4% of all loans last 12 months.
  • Most borrowers make monthly loan payment in the range of 0-400 dollars. 150-175 dollars is the most common monthly loan payment. There are very small amount of monthly payment higher than 1000 dollars. I have limited the range of X axis to display the plot properly.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

Multivariate Exploration¶

Question 16: Does Term play a part on the relationship between MonthlyLoanPayment and LoanOriginalAmount?¶

In [32]:
g = sns.FacetGrid(data = loan_clean, hue = 'Term', height = 5)
g.map(plt.scatter, 'LoanOriginalAmount', 'MonthlyLoanPayment')
g.add_legend()
plt.show()

Observation 16¶

  • This plot helps to explain the visualization in Quesion 12. We know there is strong correlation between MonthlyLoanPayment and LoanOriginalAmount, but are puzzled by several line patterns with different slope. Now we can see the line patterns are corresponded to the loan term. Different loan term shows different slope.
  • The longer the term, the lower the monthly payment. Connecting this fact with Question 9, it explains why least borrowers choose 12-month term.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at your feature(s) of interest?¶

We know there is strong correlation between MonthlyLoanPayment and LoanOriginalAmount, but are puzzled by several line patterns with different slopes (see Question 12). Now we can see the line patterns are related to the loan term. Different loan term shows different slope. The longer the term, the lower the monthly payment. Connecting this fact with Question 9, it explains why the number of borrowers choose 12-month term is the least.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?¶

The correlation matrix and scatter plot matrix shown in Question 11 can be also counted as multivariate exploration. Most of the correlation coefficients do not suggest strong correlation and this has been verified in the scatter plots. To improve this project, new features need to be added for exploration.

Conclusions¶

This notebook tries to answer the questions about who and why borrows through Prosper and what affect the borrowers' APR or interest rates.

In univariate exploration, we find out most borrowers' listings are under "Debt Consolidation" category whose number outweighs the sum of all other categories. This shows the borrowers have already got debts and Prosper can provide better APR than other loan companies. Top 5 occupations in the borrrowers are "Computer Programmer", "Executive", "Teacher", "Administrative Assistant", and "Analyst". The median of the borrowers' monthly income is 4667 dollars. And most borrowers' monthly loan payment is in the range between 150-175 dollars. Nearly half of all loans were were in progress when Prosper Loan dataset was done. But in the loans which are finished, nearly 2/3 are completed. The failed loans (Changed Off, Defaulted, Past Due, Cancelled) account for 1/3 of all finished loans.

In bivariate exploration, we find monthly loan payment has strong correlation with loan's original amount. But the scatter plot of these features shows a few straight line patterns with different slopes. This has been explained by multivariate exploration and the different line patterns are caused by different length of the loan ("Term" feature).

We also find the borrowers' APR are significantly affected by their Prosper ratings. The higher the rating, the lower the APR. And the borrowers' employment status play a part in APR as well. For unemployed people, they have to afford higher APR.
